Close
Patient is a 26-year-old female who presents today with symptoms including migraine, "brain fog", fatigue, low grade fevers, and dizziness that began 6 days ago following receiving her first dose of COVID-19 vaccine. Pt. States she was tested for COVID 3 days prior to vaccine and this was negative. Pt. Says she had been sick for 6-7 days prior to taking vaccine and believes her immune system might of been weak from this. She received Moderna COVID vaccine at hospital. Her symptoms were more persistent and with more intensity for the first 3-4 days but now the symptoms are more "off and on." Her headache is posterior and the dizziness is also "more intermittent than before." Her headache is rated 4/10 at this time. She has taken OTC NSAIDS without much relief. The "dizziness" seems to occur randomly and is not aggravated by rapid positional changes. She does ingest moderate amounts of caffeine to boost her energy level while at work. She denies visual changes/focal weakness/discoordination/nausea/vomiting/abd pain/shortness of breath/wheezing. Pt. Reports that she has been very concerned about making sure she takes the right measures to help prevent getting COVID infection. She has researched the COVID vaccines, how they are made, and which are "more potent."

I had slight dizziness for 20 minutes a half hour after the injection. But that's not the issue. When the lady gave me the injection, it felt like she wiggled it around in my arm. The injection itself was surprisingly painful. My arm hurt at first like I was punched in the arm on the first day (much like a flu vaccine). But then it got SIGNIFICANTLY worse the next day. I can move my arm, but not without a lot of pain.

26 2021-01-25 confusional state, feeling abnormal, fear, disorientation, delirium I am not sure if the event that happened Sunday was directly related to the vaccine at all since it ... Read more
Close
I am not sure if the event that happened Sunday was directly related to the vaccine at all since it happened two days later, or if it was just a coincidence, or if the vaccine was just a physical stimulus trigger. I just wanted to let you know just in case! But out of nowhere, I had an episode (never had it before) where I can only describe it as what it might feel like to be drugged. I was delirious, confused, disoriented, dizzy. I wasn't able to leave bed without the room spinning. I had chest tightness and headache. When I would close my eyes, I would feel such head pressure that it felt like my body was on a boat during a tsunami. I would feel shaking and spinning inside my head. I never felt anything like it before. I was struggling to stay conscious. In the moment, I remember wondering if it was a brain aneurysm or if I was dying. I was scared, felt like I needed to call for help, but I was unable to. I allowed myself to fall asleep/lose consciousness (not sure which), and when I woke up an hour or so later, I felt a little better. I was still a bit confused on what happened and felt physically weak, but the episode had resolved. Hours later, I called the on-call service at my doctor's office because I couldn't shake the feeling that something wasn't right. She instructed me to go to the emergency room. By the time I got to the emergency room and got seen, this was a good 8-9 hours or so after the episode occurred. The PA-C at the ER ran bloodwork and a uranalysis (I do not know what he tested for since I was not given the results), as well as had me hooked up to a heart monitor. He said everything looked normal and that he would not run a CT scan since he did not think I had an aneurysm or anything indicating the need to expose me to radiation to perform a CT. I asked for an EEG and he said they do not do that at the emergency room. He discharged me to follow up with my PCP. While in the ER, I would have episodes of staring blankly into space at random, uncontrollably, and for an undetermined amount of time. I told the doctor, and he wasn't concerned. Yesterday (01/25/2021) I met with my PCP via telehealth and explained everything. He thinks it could have been my previously-diagnosed conversion disorder; however, I have not had that manifestation of it in the past. I expressed to him that I am very scared to get the second dose of the vaccine since I do not know if this event is related or not, and I do not want to die. I have two cats who need me! He did not think it was related to the vaccine, since it happened two days after the injection. But conversion disorder comes on with physical/mental/emotional trauma/stimuli. For the most part, I was feeling okay mentally. The vaccine was the only change to my normal routine. My previous conversion disorder effect was the loss/difficulty of the ability to swallow. I have not had an episode of that in years. The symptoms I experienced seem to be possible manifestations of the disorder when I did some research, but it does not fully explain what I experienced. I asked for a referral to neurology, just to be safe, and I have the appointment tomorrow (01/27/2021). I still feel residually weak, slight chest tightness, and overall feeling off/weird. Again, I do not know if this is directly related to the vaccine, but I wanted to make you aware just in case!
26 2021-01-25 impaired work ability 12/29: severe joint pain which prevented me from working (used OTC ibuprofen to help manage symptoms... Read more
Close
12/29: severe joint pain which prevented me from working (used OTC ibuprofen to help manage symptoms), moderate sore arm, mild headache, mild nausea 12/30: severe facial nerve pain onset in evening while I was laying in bed, followed by pins and needles tingling feeling. Went to clinic on morning of 12/31 due to symptoms and lingering facial Paresthesia. Doctor recommended I not receive second dose of vaccine and tentatively diagnosed me with a mild/incomplete Bell?s Palsy or trigeminal neuralgia. Important to note that I did NOT experience any facial weakness or drooping. Did not receive any prescription medications. Paresthesia resolved within 2 days.

Close
After the first dose of the COVID vaccine, I woke up with severe neck pain. It was on the right side of my neck (opposite of my vaccine site). It was extremely severe and woke me up from my sleep. I've had miralax in the past without any issues. I've never had a vaccine adverse reaction. I have no history of atopy.

I decided sign up for the COVID-19 vaccine in order to help our world fight against this pandemic. I wanted to protect my family and friends to eradicate this virus once and for all. It was with no hesitation did I jump at the opportunity to get this vaccine when it became available to me on February 12th, 2021 at the Convention Center. As soon as I received my shot I proudly posted my photo with tears in my eyes letting the world know that we were one human closer to a COVID-19 free world. I was Moderna proud. My entire family had already received their Moderna vaccines because I come from a family of nurses, but none of them had experienced any side effects. I was confident I would be in the clear after their clear symptom free vaccine. Immediately following my vaccine my arm was a little sore, as expected. However, I did experience fatigue and mild leg cramps in my calves. One very odd symptom was that I could taste the vaccine in my mouth, like a metallic, strange taste, which I reported to my family, but everyone just laughed it off. The leg cramps went away after a day or two as well as the taste, but the fatigue continued throughout the week. I felt these symptoms were pretty average. I signed up for the V-Safe reporting system and put in my report and thought nothing of my initial vaccine symptoms. Things took a very strange turn on the morning of February 20th, 2021 at about 10am. I woke up and my face was numb, tingling all over, twitching in different parts of my face pretty severely and uncontrollably. By 4pm the tingling moved into both of my arms and hands and by 5pm it moved into both of my legs. Shortly after the cramping and twitching began in both of my legs and I lost the ability to walk, lift my legs, and just the ability to feel my legs at all. I could not walk. Obviously concerning, I thought I was originally having a reaction to a medication I had been taking for over a year called, Topamax, a nerve pain medication which can cause numbness and tingling as a side effect. I called my prescribing physician and he immediately ruled out the possibility of a reaction to this medication due to the length of time I had been on this medication, that I had not missed a dose, I had not increased or decreased the dose, and I had not experienced a reaction like this in the time that I had been taking the medication. He recommended I keep an eye on my symptoms and go to an emergency room if things worsen. Overnight, my symptoms remained the same. I woke up on Sunday, February 21st, 2021 and I still could not walk, I could not feel my legs. My legs were still twitching and cramping. My face was still numb and tingling, but the twitching had stopped in the face. My hands had stopped tingling. At this point my mother who is a nurse suggested that I call Moderna, the vaccine provider, to report a possible side effect of the vaccine. Upon contacting Moderna, the company thought that it could possibly be a reaction between the Topamax medication and the vaccine, but they had no current information about these two having any interactions. They thanked me for reporting and told me to go to an emergency room if my symptoms continued or worsen. Throughout the day on Sunday, February 21st, my symptoms remained. I was able to get to my feet, but I walking like a newborn baby giraffe or as my mother described, like a 105 year old woman. I was unable to feel my legs completely, lift them, move them without lifting them with physical help of my arms moving them. At this point on Sunday night I decided to contact my Primary Care Physician. She noted that this sounded similar to Guillain-Barre and that I sound immediately go to an Emergency Department before the symptoms get any worse. It was late on a Sunday night and I was unable to drive myself, so I waited. Overnight on Sunday into Monday I began experiencing light flashes in my eyes, heart races, lower back pain, and worsening cramping in my legs. I knew that I needed to seek treatment in an emergency room. On Monday, February 22nd, 2021 I was taken to the Emergency Room Department. They conducted blood work and a physical examination, but did not want to proceed with any MRI?s or CAT scans. The ER the doctors were baffled. They could not figure out what was causing my paralysis other than the vaccine was the only new thing that had been introduced to my body, but they could not verify or diagnose anything. They let me go with a referral to neurology. While we were sitting in the ER my cousin, a nurse anesthetist at another local hospital, called my mother who was with me with some very alarming news. Her co-worker, had experienced the same symptoms back in December and was just going through recovery after his first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. He was told by the CDC there had been 19 reported cases through the CDC where after the first dose of the vaccine people have reported numbness, tingling, and the lose of the ability to walk after receiving the first dose of the mRNA vaccine, both Moderna and Pfizer. Her co-worker was also in the same age range as myself, very healthy, young, active. He was officially diagnosed with Transverse Myletis. He has taken a full two months to regain the ability to walk and still has numb patches on his legs. He walks very slowly, but is walking. He returned to work, but cannot return to his normal life working out and being active because he does not have the strength. He was told not to get the second dose of the vaccine. There are unreported cases in this area by physicians who do not know where to turn with this information. It is hard to link these symptoms and cases because they are so obscure, but these same symptoms are occurring with those who have also had COVID-19. When I was being seen for an EMG test of my legs the physician performing the test said to us, ?I have a patient who received the vaccine and has the symptoms, maybe I should report it!?. My Grandmother?s physician just last week just sent a patient of hers with the same symptoms to neurology. I think this uncommon side effect is more common than is being reported and no one knows where to turn with the information. I finally got into the head of Neurology. I was told, ?it?ll probably get better?, basically saying that they don?t know what they can do and they are at a loss for knowing what this is and why this is happening to people after the first dose of the mRNA vaccine. Doctors don?t have answers and the vaccine companies aren?t offering information to help link these side effects together. The physician told me not to proceed with the second dose of the vaccine due to neurological side effect that I have had. I should benefit from the first dose and it is not safe for me to get the second dose from this side effect. I was unable to walk for weeks since this began on Feb. 20th. It is just now that this week I am slowly able to move my legs, but they are still very numb and heavy. I haven?t been able to drive or live my normal life. I cannot use stairs, walk long distances, stand for very long periods of time. I am twenty-eight years old and I walk like an eighty year old woman, wobbly. I have reported my case to CDC, V-SAFE, Moderna. The CDC said they would be in contact with me due to my report of extreme adverse side effects via the V-SAFE report, but I have not heard anything from them as of today. These are the uncommon side effects that need to be heard and reported. I don?t know why they are being ignored because I have been left without answers and without hope.

Less than a week after my second dose, I started itching on my body. Where I scratched, hives would show up (I have a lot of pictures for proof if needed). Hives were painful, itchy, and consistent. I called a Teledoc and also went to Urgent Care. They prescribed me an anti-viral, antihistimines, steroid pills, and steroid topical creams. Nothing helped. I bought oatmeal lotions and oatmeal bath, but sitting in the bath irritated and inflamed my back even more. The only thing that relieved the itching and pain, was making a paste out of the oatmeal bath powder, and covering my body. That being said, I had to take off of work for the week due to the uncontrollable pain and itching. Being at home, I basically just laid in bed covered in paste. But laying in the bed for too long also inflamed my back and caused pain. The symptoms started decreasing in severity. I started using herbal topical oils instead of the paste, when I could. I had two: one with the following ingredients: Menthol 14.5%, Methyl Salicylate 30%, Inactive Ingredients: Chlorophyll, ethyl alcohol, mineral oil, rose oil. The other: Menthol, Peppermint oil, Camphor, clove oil, and cinnamon oil . Those relieved my symptoms as well. I went to see a dermatologist 5/5 since the symptoms persisted. She prescribed Xyzal, Zyrtec, and more Prednisone. Said to come back in a month if symptoms still persisted. Went back yesterday (6/9) since I am still having symptoms and she diagnosed me with chronic urticaria. My symptoms have decreased in severity in comparison to when it first started. Now (two months after my second vaccine), I still get hives when I apply too much pressure to my skin ("too much" meaning things like: putting on or taking off my watch, hanging my purse on my right arm, accidentally rubbing my arm against a desk, accidentally grazing my coffee table with my leg, etc.) At least my body isn't itchy, causing me to scratch like when it first started. But I am still having symptoms and a reation.

This is my second pregnancy and at the time of my vaccination, I was 32 weeks 6 days gestation with an estimated delivery date of 2/15/21. I tolerated the vaccine well initially with only a very minor sore arm the day after the vaccine. On 12/31/2020 (4 days after vaccination), I felt muscle fatigue around my hips and buttocks as well as significant fatigue. It seemed to improve over the course of the day and was not very noticeable for the next few days. On 1/4/21 (8 days after vaccination), my muscle fatigue in my hips, buttocks, thighs, and hamstrings bilaterally became very significant, preventing me from doing some activities that I had planned. I also had generalized fatigue. On 1/5/21, I had similar symptoms, but the muscle fatigue also began to include my shoulders bilaterally. 1/6/21, the muscle fatigue also included my neck and I was physically exhausted. 1/7/21 I started to note some improvement, and I also saw my OB who did bloodwork but also did suspect a possibly delayed reaction to my vaccine. Today (1/9/21) I am still experiencing muscle fatigue, but it does seem to be improved from several days ago.

I received Moderna vaccine on 01/06/2021. Normal pain at the injection site occured with little concern. Pain in armpit began 01/08/2021. I did not think anything of it, believing the pain to be from an ingrown hair caused by shaving or just something with the vaccine. I ignored it to spend time with family. On 01/12/2021 I noticed the pain had not subsided and deepened into the armpit causing pain to radiate from the area when lifting or moving heavy items. I palpated the area and felt a pea sized lump. It moved freely. I could not locate it again. I continued to palpate into the top of my shoulder and discovered a large lump in the clavicle area. It is painful to apply pressure. I knew these areas to be part of the lymphatic system. I also did research on side effects of the Moderna vaccine but observed most people to have lymph node symptoms for only 24-48 hours within three days of receiving the vaccine then they subside. I made an appointment that same day, 01/12/2021, with Dr. at clinic to be examined. At first, Dr was dismissive of my symptoms. Dr did physically examine my areas of complaint and scheduled an ultrasound for 01/15/2021 at Hospital. On 01/13/2021 I noticed the injection site began to ache again. On 01/14/2021 I awoke from a nap at 6pm. I began showering for work when I felt a burning, itchy sensation on my inner left bicep. I observed two red spots on my inner left bicep close to my armpit with a red rash below the two red spots. I palpated the red spots to find a large and slightly smaller lump under the skin corresponding with the red spots. The rash itches. As of 01/15/2021, the ultrasound had to be rescheduled by the hospital as their ultrasound technician cannot make it into work because of a blizzard. I now have two lumps in the clavicle area that alternate swelling and reducing in size. I've been taking tylenol every four hours when I'm awake to control the pain. The ones in my clavicle now cause tension in the left side of my neck. I've also applied warm compresses on the affected sites. It helps lessen the swelling for a bit but does come back.

I had to call out sick from work on 1/22. Worked a 7L shift on 1/24 and at about 2000 noticed a petechial rash on bilateral lower extremities that spread up to lower abdomen. Called on-call L&D Doctor and she advised for me to be assessed at L&D triage. I was then admitted for 4 hours due to my rash and further workup concerning for DIC, thrombocytopenia and/or other possibilities. My petechial rash was very concerning for coagulation disorders and prompted many lab draws to be obtained. My labs showed elevated AST & ALT that were previously normal, low platelet count (thrombocytopenia), protein in urine, elevated alk phos. I was discharged around 0100 for further workup the following day. On 1/25 I went to clinic to have more labs done per Doctor. 1/26 at about 0830 I was called by my OB Docotor to immediately go back to Labor & Delivery triage to be admitted for what she thought was preeclampsia based on my labs from 1/25 and 1/24. I was again admitted for about 4 hours for monitoring of baby, and myself for preeclampsia. My labs were still elevated and out of range mirroring preeclampsia, but my blood pressure was stable, so I was discharged around 1300. I followed up with labs at clinic on 1/28 and again on 2/2 as well as with home blood pressure monitoring. My labs on 2/2 showed everything back to normal, causing the doctors involved in my care to believe this was an adverse event due to the moderna covid vaccine. As a result I missed one day of work, was admitted to the hospital twice, and had 4 days of lab draws which will result in an excess of medical bills.

The patient's medical history included unspecified teeth work on Dec 2020. Concomitant product used by the patient medroxy progesterone acetate for an unknown indication. On 15 Feb 2021, the patient received the first dose of their two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: unknown) for prophylaxis of COVID 19 infection. On 15 Mar 2021, prior to the onset of events the patients received second dose of their two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: unknown) for prophylaxis of COVID 19 infection. On 15 Mar 2021, on the day of her second dose, the patient felt confused, disoriented and could not even drive herself back to home. On 16 Mar 2021, the patient developed fever and the worst body aches ever she had. The patient noticed that her teeth became sensitive to both cold and hot. The patient stated that her teeth were shocking in the whole mouth and the two teeth which had some work was hurting. The patient felt like something was poking her face almost like her face was paralyzed and felt nauseous. The event facial paralysis was considered medically significant and serious. The patient tried acetaminophen which did not work and then took ibuprofen which was effective. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not applicable. The outcome of the events confusion, disorientation, could not drive herself/impaired driving ability, nausea, fever/pyrexia, body aches/general body pain, sensitive teeth/hyperaesthesia teeth, poking in face/facial paralysis were unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information which shows a temporal association between the use of the mRNA-1273 and the reported events and excluding all other etiology, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Nausea and fever are consistent with the vaccine safety profile.

April 6th, 2021 Today at about 2:43pm, one of our technicians came to me and stated that a customer (employee too) had just got her second COVID-19 shot (Moderna), and she was at her car and not feeling well. The patient's co-worker had told us that her finger tips were numb and that she had a headache. The technician asked the customer to come back in, which she did and sat down in a chair immediately in front of me. I went directly to talk to her, as another technician was helping in the clinical services room, drawing up more shots. I asked the patient how she was feeling, and what she was feeling. She said she did not feel well, that her finger tips were numb, and she had this incredible pounding in the back of her head, and she ran her hand over the lower back part of her head and neck. She looked down and I asked her again how she was doing, she said not well, that she was beginning to get light headed and was looking a little pale. I called to the pharmacy team for help, to clear out the clinical services room and asked the technician to help me slowly walk her to the room. As we got her in the room I asked her if she would be ok to lay down on the floor and put her feet up in a chair, briefly explaining that this would help with the dizziness and keep her safe should she faint, because she would already be on the floor. another technician popped in and asked her if she could get her a cold cloth for her forehead, Patient said yes and the technician did so. an employee was working at the computer and just quietly stayed working (for another store). I moved around him and got the Blood Pressure Machine. I asked the patient if it would be ok it I monitored her blood pressure, she said yes. Patient was always 100% coherent and helped move her arm for me. I asked the employee for a piece of paper to document the reading, but the technician ran and got me one. Her first set of vitals were high. I marked them down and the employee told me the time. I just sat on my knees next to the patient for a while and tried to comfort her. I asked her a couple of times if she felt any change, and she said yes, Shot given 2:40pm 2:45pm BP 149/99 Pulse 71 SX: fingers numb, pounding in the back of her head cool cloth placed on forehead calmed area down & quietly talked to the patient to determine how she was doing ************************************************ (Patient volunteered that she had just gotten tested for COVID-19 and that she tested negative.) I asked patient how she was feeling and she said that she was feeling a little worse. She said she was starting to get the shakes. I asked her if she had gotten anything to eat on her lunch and she said no. I asked her if she felt like it and if her BP was good, how would she like a sip of juice. ******************************************** I asked the patient how she was feeling and she stated that her tight felt ever so slightly tight, but she said "I am asthmatic, and it did not feel any different than what she had experienced before. I took her BP/P again... 2:55pm BP 157/105 Pulse 68 I looked at the employee and he looked at me, and I told the patient that I would be right back. I quickly went and consulted with the technician and we decided that we should call 911 due to the increased in BP, pulse lower and the change in symptoms. The technician called 611 and talked to an employee and I called 911 and explained what was going on and what our need was. (The technician and I quickly discussed that neither of us felt that she was having an allergic reaction, just an adverse reaction, Epi was not called for. ) Employee stated that the clinic recommended we give her Benadryl. I did a fast check w/ the technician, it was not on our standing order/ protocol. Antihistamines can exacerbate asthma.) Then I went back to the patient. By the time I had gotten off the phone with 911, 2 more employees were in the room, and the patient was just getting off the phone with her father. Once I got positioned in the room, one employee left, I asked one employee sit down in a chair and the other employee was by the door leading to the pharmacy. I told the patient that we had called for an ambulance. I briefly explained due to her BP/P and her symptoms changing. I asked her if she wanted another cool cloth and she said yes. I asked an employee to get one for her from the sink in the pharmacy. I was again kneeling at her side. I saw her eyes well up with tears and a few tears were running down her face. I asked another employee to get me a paper towel, which he did, and I handed it to the patient. I tried to reassure her that things would be ok and this was just to ensure that she was safe. She stated that she felt a little nauseated. I then took her BP/P again. 3:05PM BP 146/99 P 66 2 employees and I remained with the patient, all calm and I made sure she knew we were there for her. I am not sure the time the EMTs arrived, but another employee let us know and we opened the door to let them in. They asked the patient a lot of questions and I gave them my sheet of what I had recorded for her blood pressure and pulse (BP/P). They asked the patient if they would help her into a sitting position, she said yes, but it was an awkward position, so I asked the patient if it would be ok if I helped support her back, she said yes, and I did just that. I stayed with the patient until they got her situated on the gurney and I helped cover up her legs. I went back to work when the EMT's wheeled the patient away. The BP/P is the best of my recollection, as the EMT's took my sheet of paper. At no time did the patient ever exhibit difficulty breathing, labored breathing or any change in her breathing. She was calm and her chief complaint was the numbness in her fingers and the pounding headache at the back of her head.

On April 15th, the otherwise healthy 30 year old daughter of my cousin passed away in a hospital from a massive stroke and seizures related to encephalitis of unknown cause. She recovered easily from Covid19 back in November of 2020, along with several of her close friends and family members with no lingering effects. She initially complained of mild nausea and vomiting but quickly developed a severe headache prompting her to visit the local ER where she received treatment for a migraine. Due to dangerously high intracranial pressure, she suffered a stroke with paralysis of her left side and a seizure. Multiple lesions were noted on her brain via MRI. A shunt was inserted to relieve the pressure, she was intubated and placed into a deep coma from which she would never awaken. Despite these medical interventions and pharmacological interventions, the pressure did not subside. A craniotomy was performed the following Saturday as a last ditch effort to relieve the unrelenting pressure in her brain. The craniotomy was able to reduce the pressure but it was too late. There was no longer any brain activity and my cousin's daughter was removed from life support after they were able to say their goodbyes. The medical examiner will be examining her brain to attempt to find a cause but that report may take 6 months.

Close
On Saturday, February 20, 2021 I received my first dose of Moderna Lot# 024M20A. I was detained for 30 minutes due to having a sulfa allergy and then released. There were no concerns that day. My arm was very sore, which I was aware of could happen for a couple of days and then things seemed to clear up. Sunday, February 28th, I woke up at 5 in the morning with a severe red, itchy rash that covered my arms, legs, chest, back, and scalp. I took Benadryl every 4 hours until 8pm in which symptoms grew worse and I drove myself to the Emergency Department. Upon examination, the doctor diagnosed that this was a rash for nonspecific skin eruption. I was administered dexAMETHasone sodium phosphate (PF) (Decadron, EPINEPHrine (Adrenalin), and famotidine (Pepcid) at 10:32 pm. The epinephrine was supposed to relieve symptoms within thirty minutes and was administered into my left upper arm. It did not. They informed me that the steroid they gave me would take an additional 4-6 hours to kick in and would last 2-3 days. After detaining me to observe my body's reaction to the medicine; I was released approximately at 11:30 pm. They told me to continue taking Benadryl. At the end of the visit my vitals were as following: blood pressure: 113/69, weight 205 lbs, temperature 98.2 degrees F, pulse 91, respiration 18, oxygen saturation 99%. I was only able to sleep 3 hours that night, wake up off and on due to severe inflammation and horrible itching. Due to the lack of relief by the provided medication I began taking lukewarm oatmeal baths combined with cool showers every hour to help alleviate the itch. This helped to make the itching less strong but did not alleviate it all together. In between showers (no soap) I applied Calamine lotion and aloe vera lotion on every other rotation. These combined efforts helped to keep me from scratching as much as possible. I was not able to go to work on Monday (3/1/21). Throughout the day of Monday, I continued to take repeated showers, baths, and apply lotion. I continued to take Benadryl as directed on the package. My rash did not seem to be clearing up and I was just able to make the itching slightly bearable. This continued through the night, where yet again I was only able to sleep 2-3 hours. On Tuesday morning (3/2/21) I awoke with my back inflamed and hopped immediately into a cold shower. Upon my husband?s examination the rash suddenly had worsened. There were more breakouts of tiny itchy spots everywhere and the itching was unbearable. As soon as Urgent Care opened at 8:00 am I checked myself in. My primary care physician was unable to secure me an appointment for the day and I couldn?t take it any longer. At this point I was so uncomfortable I started to feel helpless and hopeless. I was seen by the PA-C at approximately 8:20 am. I informed the doctor that I had not had any changes to my diet, my medications, my laundry detergent, dish soap, body wash, lotions, toothpaste, deodorant, perfume, or any other thing of that nature. I had not been sick this year at all and I had not had any other vaccinations nor traveled outside of the country. Nor have I been quarantined this year because of Covid. I also told about my good friend in. She stated that exactly the same amount of days later after her Covid shot; she had a rash too but her rash disappeared after a couple of days and she did not need medical care for it nor was it itchy. I informed the doctor that the only thing I had that was new to my body was the first dose of the Moderna vaccine. It was the doctor's opinion that this was an allergic drug rash. The doctor also firmly recommended that I do not get the second dose of the Modern vaccine. He said that there have been credible reports released of delayed reactions such as this and even though there wasn?t a way yet to medically prove it, due to all of the information provided he strongly felt this was a reaction to the vaccine. My rash was so bad that as he lifted my shirt to look at it, even he was appalled. I was administered methylPREDNISolone sodium succ (PF) (SOLU-Medrol) in the buttocks at 9:03 for treatment. I was also prescribed a predniSONE 50 mg tablet to take once daily with food for the next 8 days. Additionally I was prescribed triamcinolone 0.5% ointment to apply 2-3 times daily as needed for itching relief. I was released at approximately 10 am after an observation period to make sure I did not have a reaction to the methylPREDNISolone sodium succ (PF) (SOLU-Medrol). Upon my release I was given a doctor?s note to not return to work until Thursday 3/4/21. I was told to keep taking Benadryl along with the new medication to treat the rash. Approximately around noon hours later, I noticed an improvement in the rash on my arms. They were less spotty, inflamed and itchy. By 5 pm my legs were improving and were less itchy and spotty as well. I picked up my predniSONE prescription at 5:30 and took 1 tablet by mouth with food at approximately 6pm. By late evening, the itching on my back, chest, and scalp had decreased by 50% although they were still majorly broken out. I did not take any more oatmeal baths but I did take a cool shower before bed using no soap. On Wednesday 3/3/21 I awoke at 7 am. I was able to sleep through the night and only woke up twice to reapply aloe vera lotion. My arms and chest were no longer itchy but my back, scalp, shoulders, and behind my knees were still itchy. I was still very broke out on my chest and back but the skin did not appear to be as inflamed. My arms are no longer red and the spots are very tiny and pink. I picked up my triamcinolone 0.5% ointment at 10 am in the morning due to the pharmacy needing to order it. At approximately 11:30 am I canceled my 2nd dose appointment with that was scheduled for Friday, March 19th at 1:50 pm. Thursday 3/4/21 I returned to work. I found myself to be very weak and very shaky if I stood for any amount of time. I had to work with students from my rolling chair, scooting around the classroom. Sunday 3/7/21 I seem to have my strength back and am no longer shaky when I am trying to do daily tasks. Thursday 3/11/21 It?s a week later and the bumps are finally mostly cleared up. Half a dozen remain on my shoulders and have turned into pus filled bumps almost like pimples. Thursday 3/25/21 All traces of the bumps are gone from my arms, legs, chest, and back. Only a couple of them remain now appearing to have turned into ?pimples?. My doctor prescribed me a steroid cream to help get rid of the remaining bumps.

Could not identify these specific side effects in the information available online, took a Benadryl in case it was an allergic reaction. At the time of this report, pain in right arm still present from shoulder to wrist and entire arm is tender to the touch, but pain level has lessened. Lymph nodes in right underarm swollen by 5:00 AM on 3/4/21 and swelling is still present at the time of this report. Will continue with regimen of ibuprofin as needed. * I am recovering fine at home, but I wanted to log these side effects for data collection purposes. I couldn't find any information about these side effects online and that really freaked me out, so I hope that writing this report will help people in a similar situation.

1/23/2021 - The first Moderna vaccine. I had flu like symptoms, which included fatigue, muscles aches, muscle spasms, joint aches, chills, and shortness of breath for 2-3 days afterward. 2/20/2021 - The second Moderna vaccine. The side effects were much worse, including muscle aches, abdominal pain, back pain, headache, nausea, chills, fatigue, and shortness of breath. I also found myself limping. 2/21, 2/22, 2/23 - I rested and stayed home from work. Most of my symptoms had improved by the evening of the 23rd, and I felt like the shortness of breath was also improving if I took it easy. 2/24 - I went to work where the shortness of breath became much worse after working for a couple of hours. I began to get dizzy, and my hands and feet were cold and tingling. The school nurse checked my temperature (which was normal) and oxygen levels (99%). I was sent home and told to take another day or two off. I was fine if I was sitting still and doing nothing, but talking caused me to become winded. Walking and exertion of any kind caused me to become winded. Once winded, it would take 15 minutes of sitting still to get my breathing back under control. Then I would be hit by a wave of fatigue. Also, when my breathing was bad, I walked with a limp. 2/25 - I went to the shortness of breath was still bad. They were concerned. They took a chest x-ray (which came back clear), did blood work (which was normal), and gave me a Rapid Covid test (which was negative). My oxygen levels were at 99%. They prescribed a 6 day pack of MethylPREDNISolon. If I was not better by Saturday, they wanted me to return. They also did a PCR test (this came back negative on 2/28). 2/26 - The steroid did not help, and by the evening, I was worse. I went to the ER . The doctors there were concerned about a pulmonary embolism. They did blood work (which was normal), a chest x-ray (which came back clear), and an EKG (which was normal). My vitals were good, though my blood pressure was high for me (113/64). The doctor told me to continue the steroid pack and prescribed an albuterol inhaler. I was directed to contact a pulmonary specialist on 3/1 if symptoms did not improve. The doctor wrote a note for me to work from home through 3/5. 3/1 - The shortness of breath did not improve. I almost passed out while driving after I picked up my two small children from school. I could not catch my breath in the car and started to get lightheaded. When I parked, I stayed in the car huffing and puffing for several minutes. I was seeing spot, was dizzy, and my hands and feet were tingling. When I climbed out of the car, my legs buckled beneath me. I was able to grab onto the car and not fall. I had some really bad breathing episodes between 3/1-and 3/3. At these times, the breathing was so rough, that I couldn?t even talk. It would take 30 minutes or more of sitting still for me to be able to bring my breathing under control. 3/3 - Appointment with Pulmonary Specialist. I had an appointment He ruled out asthma, as the inhaler and steroid were both ineffective. He considered anxiety, but the problem was clearly not a panic or anxiety attack. (I have experienced those before and know the difference.) He ruled that out. He ran a pulmonary function test (which was normal) and a CT scan with contrast (which was normal). The doctor wrote a note for me to work from home through 3/10. 3/4 and on - My breathing was better some days than others. The less energy I exerted, the better I did. If I did too much one day, my breathing would be worse the next day. 3/7 - Ajovy injection. I was past due for this monthly injection. Once injected, I had an allergic reaction to it for the first time ever (this was the 7th time I used it). A few minutes after the injection, the injection area had a rash and was itching like crazy. I put ice on it and took benadryl. It was fine by the next morning. 3/9 - Appointment #2 with Pulmonary Specialist. The specialist was not sure what the problem was with my breathing. I was the first patient with these vaccine side effects that he had seen. He scheduled more tests and said he wanted to read more literature. He wrote a note for me to work from home through 4/6.

Psychiatric symptoms; Talking really fast; Not being with it, acting strange; Not coherent; A spontaneous report was received from a physician who was also a 34-year-old, female patient who received Moderna's Covid-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and developed psychiatric symptoms, talking really fast, acting strange, and incoherent. The patient's medical history was not provided. Concomitant product use was not provided. The patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 026L20A) on 05 Jan 2021 in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 06 Jan 2021, she experienced psychiatric symptoms. She started talking very fast, not being with it, acting strange, and incoherent. The symptoms got progressively worse by that evening and was taken to the emergency room. She was treated with an intramuscular antipsychotic and observed overnight. On 07 Jan 2021, the patient was discharged from the hospital. Since she has been released from the hospital, she has been fine. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not provided. The events, psychiatric symptoms, talking really fast, acting strange, and incoherent, were considered resolved on 07 Jan 2021.; Reporter's Comments: This report refers to a case of 34- year-old female patient who experienced serious unexpected events psychiatric symptoms, talking really fast, "not being with it," acting strange, and incoherent 13 hours after administration of mRNA-1273, lot # 026L20A, Exp date-unknown. Based on temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the reported events and the absence of any other etiology factors, a causal association cannot be excluded.

34 2021-02-02 feeling abnormal The patient received the Moderna vaccine on January 21, 2021. She waited at the pharmacy for 15 minu... Read more
Close
The patient received the Moderna vaccine on January 21, 2021. She waited at the pharmacy for 15 minutes after receiving the vaccine to be sure she would be okay. She felt fine after 15 minutes and so left the store. As she was walking to her car in the parking lot, she started to feel "weird" as if something was very wrong but she could not figure out why she felt this way. She got in her car and drove back to work. The feeling that something was very wrong worsened during the drive and she started itching on her arms and legs approximately 25 minutes after receipt of the vaccination. She did not have a rash or hives but the itching became very intense and spread to her entire body within a few minutes. She started to feel that her throat was tight or swollen but thought perhaps it was due to something else. However, within another 15 minutes she was having difficulty swallowing and her voice changed as she was talking to patients (hoarse). The throat symptoms continued for 30 to 45 minutes and were quite uncomfortable but she did not seek medical attention. They started to resolve after 30 to 45 minutes. However, her intense itching continued for several hours. She took Benadryl but it did not help. All her symptoms resolved after several hours and she slept well. The following day, within 24 hours, she felt her throat swelling again. This lasted for a few hours but she did not seek medical care because she could breathe. She developed a temperature of 100.8 degrees Farenheit which resolved after 4 hours but then the intense itching started again and continued into the next day. She saw her PCP (third day after receiving the Moderna vaccination) and received a steroid shot and started taking Claritin 10mg daily and Pepcid 20mg twice daily which helped some but did not relieve the itching. The itching worsened again on January 26th, 2021 and she was prescribed hydroxyzine 25mg which helps but makes her extremely sleepy. She continues to have varying degrees of itching off and on since then.

The patient's medical history included anxiety and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder. Concomitant product use was not provided. On 09 Jan 2021, prior to the onset of events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 026L20A) intramuscularly in her arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 09 Jan 2021 at 13:30, immediately after receiving the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine, the patient reported having a flushing sensation and felt anxious. At 13:36 the patient's vital signs included blood pressure 131/87 mmHg, heart rate 99 beats/min, and oxygen saturation 99%. Doctor noted hives around the injection site and on contralateral arm and chest. Patient was moved to a separate room to lie down on a bed; on route to the new room, the patient developed diarrhea. Treatment included diphenhydramine. At 13:49, the patient reported having shortness of breath and throat tightness. 99%. Intramuscular epinephrine was given and 911 called. Patient left the office in stable condition with vital signs within expected range and fully conscious. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not provided. The events, flushing feeling, felt anxiety, blood pressure fluctuation, hives around injection site and contralateral arm and chest, diarrhea, shortness of breath, throat tightness and heart rate abnormal, were considered resolved.; Reporter's Comments: A spontaneous report concerns a 34-year-old, female patient who experienced serious events of shortness of breath, throat tightness and heart rate increased and non-serious events of flushing feeling, felt anxiety, blood pressure fluctuation, hives around injection site and contralateral arm and chest and diarrhea. Outcome is resolved. Based on the information provided, which indicates a strong temporal association of the reported events with the administration of mRNA-1273 vaccine, a causal association cannot be excluded. Client was administered her second dose of COVID-19 vaccine and immediately afterwards she stated her mouth was dry, her heart was racing, her throat felt dry and she found it difficult to breathe. She stated that she had the same symptoms after she received her first dose. 911 was immediately called. Her vital signs were as follows: BP=108/80, Pulse=88, Respiration=18. She denied any history of allergies but said she had asthma, for which she took Ventolin. She did not have any dizziness. The EMT personnel arrived shortly thereafter and determined she was having a panic attack. The client as well as the EMT did not think it was necessary to transport her to the hospital. They spoke with her until she felt calm and ready to leave the POD site. She was told to call 911 if the symptoms occurred again and she verbalized understanding.

At 8:00 p.m. I began to feel adverse effects. I was reading to the boys when I felt a general all-around weird feeling that almost made want to stop reading. As I kept reading, I found it at times difficult to figure out words. Which slowed down my usual reading speed. I read for 30-45 minutes and this would happen intermittently. After done reading I proceeded to tell my husband about my day and dreams. So sure, of what I was about to say but would suddenly forget. Regaining my thoughts, I would finish my story but would then suddenly forget again. I would also start tasks, like putting my dirty clothes in the hamper, but then lose focus on that task. Thinking maybe I just needed a good night?s sleep, I went to bed. Through out the night I just felt waves uneasiness. I would fall asleep but then wake back up again feeling weird. My hands were shaking, possible response to fear of the effects. I seemed to focus on my heart beat every now then making me think I might have experienced a slight rapid heart rate. I would also feel a weird intermittent fuzzy feeling that would rush from the back of my head to the front of my head. It was almost like a warning that I was going to feel bad again. Eventually, not knowing the time, I fell asleep. The next morning, I woke up at approximately 6:00 a.m. I felt fatigued mentally and physically, had a mild headache, slight fuzzy headed, slight dizziness, slight nausea and had a sore arm. I took (2) Tylenol around 9:00 a.m and decided to report my symptoms to my PCPs office and made an appointment with an available ARNP. I took (2) Tylenol again at 6:00 p.m. I felt almost back to my normal self the third day after my vaccination.

34 2021-06-09 feeling abnormal, loss of personal independence in daily activities, depression, impaired work ability, anxiety The Moderna covid vaccine was the first vaccine I ever had. On the evening of the 18th, I was sitti... Read more
Close
The Moderna covid vaccine was the first vaccine I ever had. On the evening of the 18th, I was sitting alone after work, scrolling my phone when my heart started beating very fast, hard, and irregularly. I felt pressure in my chest and a wave of tingling wash over my head. My vision went funny and grey around the edges as if I was about to pass out. It felt lie something was squeezing my heart. I sat on the floor, put my head between my knees and took deep breaths. The heart rate spikes seemed to come in waves with a feeling of pressure every few minutes. I called someone to take me to the ER and they arrived about 45 minutes after initial symptom onset. My heart rate had slowed slightly and the spikes were coming farther apart by then. It was cold in the car and it gave me chills, but I felt that it made me feel a little better. At the ER, they kept me from about 9:30 pm to after 3:00 am. My symptoms slowly abated, with heart rate spikes coming about every 15 to 30 minutes, but shorter, and not going as high. I sat there and watched the pulse monitor for abot 5 hours, varying between the 60s and 108. I was discharged after several tests without a diagnosis and told to follow up with a cardiologist in 2 days. The attending physician verbally told me the tests were normal and I was fine, but when I viewed my test results online, it said I had an abnormal ECG, left atrial inflammation, and a possible heart attack. I was uninsured at the time, so they declined to run expensive tests. I also did not have a primary care provider. Around midnight on the evening of the 20th/morning of the 21st, a similar thing occurred while I had a late night snack and watched a TV show. I did not feel as if I was going to pass out, but had regular heart rate spikes, and a rapid, irregular heartbeat with pressure in my chest. This time I also had nausea and burning in my stomach. I did deep breathing all night. Managed to doze for about an hour. This episode lasted until 6 am. I felt better then and tried to find a cardiologist, but was referred to the ER. By the time a friend took me there (around 7-7:30 am, I think), my symptoms had largely abated, but I was very fatigued and short of breath just standing. I was again discharged after testing with no diagnosis, but told to follow-up with a cardiologist. Again, I was verbally told again that the tests were normal and I was fine, but the notes said possible biatrial inflammation. By this point, my chest ached constantly. A close friend came to help take care of me on the evening of the 22nd, and I got so excited to see her that my heart rate spiked again. I lay down and did deep breathing and couldn?t talk to her or look at her until the next day without intense heart rate spikes, nausea, chest pain, and chest pressure. I saw Dr. on the 23rd. He diagnosed me with orthostatic hypotension and tachycardia. He took my pulse while sitting (about 80, which is high for me, because my average resting pulse is usually in the high 40s/low 50s), and when standing. When I stood up, my pulse went to 120 and I became short of breath. He told me to drink pedialyte, ingest a lot of salt (he declined to recommend a specific amount), wear compression stockings, exercise while lying down, and ease myself back into activity. I should also keep my feet up as much as possible. I immediately started drinking a lot of pedialyte (a gallon to a gallon and a half a day), eating salty foods, and keeping my feet elevated. I continued to be very fatigued with episodes of rapid heartbeat (though not as bad as I went to the ER for). I frequently got a squeezing feeling in my chest as if my heartbeat was irregular. I took my blood pressure regularly and it was usually low (90s/?). Anything that was remotely exciting spiked my heart rate. I could not watch TV, listen to music, game, talk on the phone, or even sit upright.All I could do was lie flat and play boring, unexciting games on my phone. This continued for weeks. I could only sleep on my back because sleeping on my side gave me a feeling that my heart was compressed and increased my heart rate. When I got out of bed, after a few seconds I would get black spots in my vision and a wave of tingling over my scalp and feel as if I were abot to pass out. Bending over and leaning on the counter for about 5-10 seconds makes this abate. My friend had made me an appointment on April 28th, so I went to this appointment because I was not feeling better and wanted a second opinion. Dr. did not communicate as well, but seemed to agree with Dr. assessment. He prescribed fludrocortisone, metaprolol, and sertraline. He told me to take the fludrocortisone for two days before starting the metaprolol. The metaprolol seemed to help. It started keeping my heart beat irregularity/spike episodes from getting as high or lasting as long. Those have slowly diminished, though I still have a lesser version of them. The metaprolol also seemed to mostly end the squeezing feeling to my heart and irregular beat. On the evening of the May 6th, my heart started beating very hard and fast. My blood pressure was 140/?. I stopped taking the fludrocortisone and ingesting salt. I also had a squeezing feeling at the bottom of my sternum. On the 7th, I was unable to take a full breath. Whenever I tried to inflate my lungs, the squeezing feeling at the bottom of my sternum would worsen and keep my lungs from expanding. If I lay flat and only took shallow breaths, I didn?t notice anything, but as soon as I sat up or tried to stand, I could barely breathe. Dr. office referred me to the ER . At the ER, my blood pressure was 160/?. I was admitted to the hospital on the evening of the 7th and discharged on the 10th. During my stay, I was able to get temporary Medicaid to cover my hospital bills. Insurance through get covered would start on the first of June. During my hospital stay, I lay flat constantly so I could breathe, and that symptom slowly lessened, though did not go away completely. I also started experiencing tension in my throat and jaw while lying flat on my back and could not find a comfortable sleeping position. I was seen by a cardiologist who ordered tests for me on the 8th and the tests were administered on the 10th. I was briefly seen by a cardiologist, that morning and he said it was possible I had a hiatal hernia that was physically irritating my heart. At that time, my admitting doctor, told me nothing matched my symptoms and maybe it was anxiety. The discharge paper listed anxiety, depression, increased risk of falls, decreased cardiac output, high risk of bleeding, and orthostatic hypotension. Verbally, I was told I was a clot risk, but it was not on my discharge papers. I was not referred to psych or prescribed medication, or referred for an endoscopy, but discharged with the exact same symptoms I had been admitted for and told to follow up with a cardiologist in a couple weeks. Over the course of the next couple weeks, without treatment, the tension in my chest slowly eased until I could breathe almost normally. Taking a deep breath still gives me a weird feeling of uncomfortableness and pressure in my chest, but only a deep one. I still get winded easily, but not fromstanding up or walking around my apartment. Bending over is hard. I started being able to carry things as long as they weren't heavy. On May 18th and June 8th, I saw a primary care provider, who ordered more tests and referred me to a pulmonologist, endocrinologist (next week and the week after), psychiatrist and psychologist (but I am having trouble finding ones who will work with my insurance). I also saw a gastroenterologist, on the 21st, was prescribed Prilosec, and scheduled an endoscopy in early July. I still have a lot of the same symptoms, some of them have lessened a little, and some are mostly gone. Fatigue is constant, shortness of breath, tightness in my throat, tightness at the bottom of my esophagus, and increased heartbeat are common. Nausea and stomach burning only occur occasionally, but I still have nearly constant discomfort at the bottom of my esophagus/top of my stomach. I constantly feel as if something is squeezing my throat. The very rapid heartbeat spikes seem to be almost entirely gone, thanks to the metaprolol, but there are still mild ones. Chest pressure occurs frequently, but usually goes away when I change position. Tightness at my jaw occurs cocurrently with the chest pressure. I can sleep on my side again, though it is still feels as if it increases my heart rate sometimes. I consider it an accomplishment that I can now sit upright most of the time most days. I sometimes have a few good hours in a day where I feel almost normal. I can walk on a flat surface for a short period of time, but going up even a slight incline causes heartbeat spikes and a feeling of my heart being squeezed and I have to stop immediately. Harder work like carrying heavy groceries or an extended period walking around a store would be impossible for me. I still get black spots in my vision when I stand up, but only sometimes and have just kind of gotten used to it and expect to have to stop and bend over. Sitting upright without back support is uncomfortable and slumping at all increases the pressure at the bottom of my esophagus. I am a massage therapist, but have been unable to work since this started. I can?t even take care of myself without the assistance of friends. I still don?t have a diagnosis that explains my symptoms.

I found this odd, but didn't notice any swelling or difficulty breathing. I noticed my heart beating faster and wondered if my body was subconsciously anxious about the numb feeling even though I didn't feel worried because I was breathing fine. Very suddenly my heart started to pound very hard, my entire laryngopharynx went numb and I felt like a deck of cards was sitting in the back of my throat. I looked at the clock, it was 5:07. I started to feel dizzy and weak, my heart felt like it was about to explode, my hands were suddenly cold, clammy and shaking, I started to get sharp stomach pains similar to other anaphylactic events, but still no effects on my breathing. Moderna Covid-19 Vaccine EUA I received the 2nd shot of the Moderna Covid-19 vaccine around 9:25 am on 2/5/2021, after about 10 minutes I became hot and lightheaded. Immediately after that I started getting tingling and numbness bilaterally in my hands and fingers with a heavy sensation. My heart also started racing. The nurses put me in a wheelchair and escorted me upstairs to the ER. In transit my face and throat/neck started getting tingling as well. By the time we reached the ER waiting room (9:42 am) I got the shakes/chills and was very cold. I continued having the shakes for several minutes. By the time I was brought back into the triage area (9:50 am) my legs from the shin to feet bilaterally started going numb/tingly as well. I started having a cyclical reaction. I would shake/have the chills for about 5 minutes (without any tingling/numbness in extremities), after that I would get a full body flushing sensation with feeling of lightheadedness and nausea, followed by numbness/tingling in both hands and feet. Then the cycle would repeat itself for several hours. I continued to have a heavy sensation of my hands and feet until about 10:15 am. After that the heaviness sensation did not accompany the tingling/numbness that persisted. I was hooked up to IV fluids and IV benadryl at 10:45 am. By 12:30 I finally stopped getting the chills/shaking sensation but I had a consistent body flushing followed by tingling/numbness in my hands and feet (mostly hands/arms) about every 5 minutes. Around 1 pm I all symptoms had stopped. The doctor said all my tests and blood work looked good. I was discharged from the hospital around 2:45 pm with instrustions to followup with primary doc or return to the ER if symptoms got worse. At 5:30 pm that evening all my symptoms came back, started with chills and then full body flushing sensation followed by tingling/numbness in both arms/hands bilaterally. I also had a hot sensation up the entire side of my left arm (injection site arm) up to my ear. I took 2 500 mg tablets of Tylenol and 2 25 mg tablets of benadryl at 6:20. By 6:40 I was starting to feel a little better with less shaking and less body flushing/tingling. Symptoms seemed gone by 7 pm. I went to bed at 9 pm and woke up around 10:30 pm to my body flushing and my hands going tingling/numb. I tried to sleep, but could not. Around 11:30 pm I took 1 500 mg tablet of Tylenol and 2 25 mg tablets of benadryl. I woke up the next morning (2/6/2021) with no numbness/tingling shaking or body flushing. I felt extremely exhausted and sore. That day my symptoms did not return. I woke up on Sunday 2/7/2021 with no symptoms, but around 8:30 am I had a lightheaded episode and hot sensation with a feeling of nausea. I then started to get tingling in my face, mouth and lips. It persisted for 2.5 hours until I decided to take Benadryl (2 25 mg tablets). about 30 minutes after taking medication the tingling stopped. It did not return.

The patient's medical history include severe allergies NOS. Concomitant product included Benadryl prior to the second dose of the vaccine. On an unknown date, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number not provided). On 22-Feb-2021, prior to the onset of the symptoms, the patient received their second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: 011M20A) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 22-Feb-2021 , immediately after receiving vaccine, the patient experienced an allergic reaction with generalized itching, swollen eyes, skin abrasions, throat swelling, chest tightness, chest erythema, elevated heart rate, nausea, vomiting, headache, anxiety attack and vaginal/vulvar rash. Treatment for the events included Phenergan, IV antihistamine, IV steroids, prednisone, hydroxyzine hydrochloride and EpiPen. The patient received both scheduled doses of mRNA-1273 prior to the event, therefore, action taken with the drug in response to the event is not applicable. The outcome of the events, allergic reaction with generalized itching, swollen eyes, skin abrasions, throat swelling, chest tightness, chest erythema, elevated heart rate, nausea, vomiting, headache, anxiety attack and vaginal/vulvar rash, was unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Patient's prior severe allergy history may have been contributory for the occurrence of the allergic reaction and associated events. Additionally, This report refers to a case of an inappropriate schedule of product administration for mRNA-1273, lot #011M20A.

I had my first vaccine (Moderna, V00120) on February 26. About a week after, I started feeling paresthesia, numbness in the right side of my body, specifically in the right leg and arm, and I started having difficulties walking. Since the symptoms persisted, I went to the Dr. on March 23. I told him that I thought my symptom were out of the blue and I linked them to the vaccine, so I was visiting him to see if I should put my second vaccine in those circumstances, few days after. Doctor said that there was no relation between nerve damage and the vaccine and he recommended me to put it. He sent me test thinking that could be multiple esclerosis. I did my brain MRI on Thursday 25 and on Friday March 26 I put my second dose. About a week after the second dose my symptoms were dramatically aggravated. I first started experiencing a sudden fatigue that didn't even allow me to hold the cellphone or a spoon and I had to lie down. I couldn't hold my 8 months daughter because I felt such a strong weakness. This fatigue didn't allow me to work. This happened few days in a raw for few hours. On April 8th I started to feel needles and strong neuropathic pain that I had never experience in my whole life. On April 9th in the evening I had a massive crisis. I started to feel a sudden having a lot of cold, starting shivering and then chattering teeth and strong headache. (Same reaction I had 12 hours after putting the second dose of the vaccine). I had to lie down in bed and my husband had to cover me with a jumper and eiderdown, but I still was cold. I couldn't stop shivering. Then I had difficulty swallowing. And the worst part started when I felt all over my body an intense pins and needles, burning, electricity, very profoundly and spread all over in a very intense way., I thought I was dying. I started panicking, I didn't have control over my body. I had difficulty breathing and such a weakness that didn't make me speak because I couldn't stop chattering my teeth. Was the worst life experience ever until that moment. The situation lasted about 90 minutes and then went away. The next day, Sunday April 10th, I spent the whole day in bed to rest, but at night time I experienced the same crisis as the night before. It started with the sudden cold as well. After that I didn't have more crises but the pins and needles pain remains and it made it difficult to sleep because of the pain and discomfort and I wonder if I would have it my entire life. I returned to the doctor. To a different one specialized in multiple esclerosis. Brain MRI came out negative but it was done one day before the second dose, so we cannot be sure. I did 3 MRI of my whole spine and some muscular tests to check the response of the nerves. They also took 8 tubes of blood. We are waiting for the results but doctor think is Guillain Barrel syndrome. She thinks I am suffering peripheral neuropathy.

On 08-Jan-2021, prior to the onset of events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (lot number: 011L20A) in the left non-dominant arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 08-Jan-2020, the patient received vaccine, which was of lack of correct administration as it was injected in the fat and not in the muscle and injection which was appears to be lower than where normally given. On the same date, after administration of vaccine, the patient had experienced swollen arm (swelling), hives on the back, 2.5in red circle, didn't feel good, was tired and couldn't process things well. On 18-Jan-2021, 10 days after the administration of vaccine, the patient had developed very large-red allergic reaction at the injection site with perfect circle and was hot to the touch. Treatment for the event included paracetamol (acetaminophen) and loratadine. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events were not provided. The outcome of events didn't feel good, hot to the touch, hives on the back, tired and very large, red (2.5/3in circle) allergic reaction at the injection site was unknown. The event lack of correct administration, injection appears to be lower than where normally given, was injected in the fat and not in the muscle was considered to be resolved on 08-Jan-2021. The event swollen arm/hardness was considered to be resolved on 09-Jan-2021. The event couldn't process things well was considered to be resolved on 15-Jan-2021.; Reporter's Comments: This spontaneous report refers to a case of a 37-year-old female patient who experienced non-serious events of lack of correct administration/injection appears to be lower than where normally given/was injected in the fat and not in the muscle ( inappropriate route of vaccine administered), didn't feel good, couldn't process things well, hot to the touch, hives on the back, swollen arm/hardness, tired and very large, red (2.5/3in circle) allergic reaction at the injection site.. All events excluding (large-red allergic reaction at the injection site with perfect circle hot to the touch) developed on the same day after the administration of the mRNA-1273 vaccine (lot # 011L20A, expiration date-unknown). The event of large-red allergic reaction at the injection site with perfect circle which was hot to the touch developed 10 days after the vaccine administration. Based on the information provided which includes a temporal association, a causal association between the administration of the vaccine and the other reported events cannot be excluded. Tiredness, redness and hives are consistent with the safety profile of the vaccine. The event of inappropriate route of vaccine administered is considered not applicable.

No treatment information was provided. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported. I am still not completely recovered. I am feeling ill and chest pain with tightness, but at home now. I go back to my cardiologist for a repeat EKG and repeat bloodwork this week.

38 2021-05-20 impaired work ability, loss of personal independence in daily activities, sleep disorder I am a nurse practitioner, so as a healthcare worker, I received a very early vaccine. I have had li... Read more
Close
I am a nurse practitioner, so as a healthcare worker, I received a very early vaccine. I have had little time to report what happened to me but not that it remains an issue I think I need to do so. I had a very serious initial reaction and am now having chronic problems likely related to my vaccine. I received my first dose of Moderna 12/27/20 at POD lot# 025J20A and my second dose 1/24/21 at POD lot#029L20A. After the first vaccine within a few hours I had significant injection site and arm pain. By the time I went to bed that night I could barely lift my arm over my head it was so stiff and warm. The arm was very painful, and I required Ibuprofen 800 mg TID for 3 days to control the pain. I did not have systemic symptoms from the first vaccine. After the second vaccine, within hours I had systemic symptoms of fatigue, generalized aches in my muscles and severe arm pain in the injection arm. I received the vaccine in the afternoon. I went to bed that night and woke up suddenly at 3 am, about 14 hours later. I had severe myalgias and rigors. I was barely able to move. I was not able to walk or perform fine or gross motor tasks without difficulty. I was unable to dress myself or get up to go to the bathroom. I required almost fulltime care from my husband for three days. On day 4 I developed severe headaches nausea and vomiting. The muscles still ached but I was able to walk and move again. My fine motor was still impaired for a total of 7 days. I was out of work for 8 days and did not feel 100% well for 12-14 days after the vaccine. As the symptoms started to resolve on day 5, I believe I had a mild case of Rhabdomyolysis as my urine was very dark almost brown and there was sediment in the toilet. There was no blood in my urine and no dysuria. I did a urine dip at work and it had protein and ketones but no bacteria. The specific gravity was very concentrated. I did not check my renal function at that time. My renal function a few weeks later was normal Cr 0.88. GFR 85. The dark urine and sediment lasted for about 2-3 days. I was drinking lots of water through this time-period and during then I was very ill. I was not seen at a hospital and rather I treated myself at home. During the above week was the first time I ever had neck or back pain. It did subside but I still had a dull aching in my neck after all of this. I had two episodes, one in late January and one in mid-February of left neck being very sensitive to touch, felt warm, and my ear was very hypersensitive to touch as well. It felt almost like shingles but there was never a rash and I took Acyclovir 800 mg TID for 3-5 days without relief. It subsided each time after about 7 days. This was on the same side of my body on the left as the vaccine was. In the end of March 2021 I began with left trapezoid pain in the same side of the body. I had some numbness in that arm as well so I saw orthopedics and received an MRI of my left brachial plexus which showed C3-4, C4-5, and C6-7 disc herniations that had not been present before. If the herniations were present in the past they were acutely inflamed by the inflammatory process the vaccine caused in my body. The MRI also showed significant and specifically left cervical and left axillary adenopathy this being the side of my vaccine. The pain spread beyond my trapezoid and become progressively worse into my neck and upper back only on the left side. The entire left side of my spine both cervical and thoracic was painful but the right side unaffected. It was very sharp nerve like pain shooting and running up into my head and anterior neck. Another MRI was done of the full cervical spine this time confirming these same herniations, but the discs appear to be pulling to the left with isolated left inflammatory process. The nerve pain became so severe that last week I began having numbness in that left arm and numbness into the left side of my face. A stat MRI of my brain only shows T2 flare pattern consistent with sequela of an inflammatory process of unknown origin. The foraminal stenosis at these spinal levels are very mild and do not explain my symptoms very well. Spine specialist reports that there can be symptoms of this nature but usually not with this mild of a pathology. The facial numbness has been identified as a trigeminal neuropathy of cervical origin but is rarely documented in medical journals and not seen by these spine specialists. There is a very significant amount of left sided nerve over stimulation, inflammation and adenopathy that is not explained. I have never had any spine or neck pain in my life before this and I have no history of traumatic events to explain this sudden change in my condition. I truly feel that ever since I received the Moderna vaccine and had that very severe reaction, my body has been in a constant inflammatory phase and there has been nerve pain in and around only the left upper side of my body where the vaccine was placed. I am scheduled on Monday for epidural spinal injections as I have been unable to find pain relief with any other therapies including dry needling, physical therapy, traction, tramadol, muscle relaxers, oral steroid bursts, etc. I know this may be a very strange and unique case, but I can say confidently that I believe the vaccine stimulated this entire cascade of events. If someone could please contact me related to this, I would appreciate it.

39 2021-04-07 insomnia Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA I noticed raised itchy bumps and redness on my left arm at injection si... Read more
Close
Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA I noticed raised itchy bumps and redness on my left arm at injection site the morning after my shot, they could have been shortly after I was vaccinated, but I was really only looking for any issues that might be life threatening. Over the following two weeks, the bumps/itchiness worsened and spread across all of my body except at my hands, feet, face, and lower back. Nearing the end of the second week, as the conditions worsened my skin felt painful all over (like a very bad sun burn). Due to the discomfort, I was largely unable to sleep during this period and had difficulty focusing on work. At week one I started taking Benadryl and applying lotion on my skin. I informed my PCP as well as the clinic that administered the vaccine of my condition. The clinic said they could do nothing unless my condition was life threatening. My PCP advised that an itchy rash is a rare side effect of the vaccine but that it would get better typically within 8-12 days. He also advised on taking an additional over the counter antihistamine along with the Benadryl, which I did. None of the antihistamines made the conditions better, they continued to worsen. I started taking Ibuprofen for the discomfort and pain. By the end of the second week, my rash became more painful especially at my chest, neck, and ears - the skin became quite red and looked a bit like a burn. At this point I did not believe I was having a safe reaction and reached out to my PCP and vaccine clinic once more. I was not able to reach my PCP but did connect virtually with an online doctor who reviewed photos of my skin and prescribed a topical steroid. Doctor advised I see a specialist in person, with concern that taking an oral steroid might mitigate the effects of the vaccine. I alerted the clinic that I would be seeing this specialist and they advised that I instead go to urgent care. The following day (4/6/21), I did both. Healthcare facility provided an oral steroid and did not think it would impact the vaccination. The Specialist did not want to prescribe a steroid in concern that it would mitigate the effects of the vaccine. He advised to endure the rash another 1-2 weeks. Later that night, I could not bare the pain and starting taking the oral steroid. Within 24 hours I started feeling some relief. I am on day three of six of the steroid and each day the pain, itching, and rash are getting better. I will have a meeting in person at the clinic where I received my vaccine this Friday for a doctor to assess my rash and determine if it is appropriate for me to take a second dose healthcare facility requested this meeting.

Vitals taken at 0910 were 120/85, 73bmp. She reported that her symptoms were beginning to alleviate. EMS arrived at 0915 followed by paramedics at 0918. Vitals at 0918 were 110/68, 60 bmp, 100% SpO2. Vitals at 0922 were 131/98 and 62 BPM. Paramedics discussed possibility of it being a panic attack but recommended going to hospital to be monitored - discussed spouse driving vs paramedic transport. At this point client shared that her HR at approx 0905 was 45 bpm per her wearable device. EMS discussed how this is another indicator of anaphylaxis and recommended ambulance transport. Client agreed and she was transported at 0930.

I took and Advil which did help. I was able to sleep about 3am and then I slept a ton and had to miss work the next day. My left arm on the upper side and back was incredibly sore. I couldn't even lay on my left side, the selling persisted for about a week. I have had way more fatigue since then. 2 upper respiratory infections back to back. I do not get sick like that ever. I just found out that I am now pregnant.

Received 2nd dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine EUA. Caused central nervous issues similar to other allergic reactions I've had from some antibiotics. Heart racing, shortness of breath, panic attacks. Physically unable to control shaking. This started Tuesday a couple hours after the vaccine and lasted until Saturday (4 days).

Chills, fever, severe headache, nasea. Took ibuprofen, cold compress to head, blanket for chills. Chills and nausea lasted for 6 or 7 hours, Fever lasted for 48 hours. Headache lasted for 60 hours. Very sore arm at injection site which lasted for about 72 hours.
